net.proteusframework.ui.miwt.component.composite

Class ClickToEditComponent

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.proteusframework.ui.miwt.component.ComponentImpl
      • net.proteusframework.ui.miwt.component.Container
        • net.proteusframework.ui.miwt.component.composite.ClickToEditComponent
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    PropertyChangeListener, Iterable<Component>, EventListener, LocaleContextSource, Component, ListCellRenderer, ParentComponent, TableCellRenderer, TreeCellRenderer, ActionListener

    public class ClickToEditComponent
extends Container
implements ActionListener
    A component that wraps another to allow it to be clicked to edit. When in "editing" mode, the component is enabled / marked editable; otherwise, the component is disabled. This is designed to be used with Editable components like the Field but can be used with any component.
    Author:
    Russ Tennant (russ@i2rd.com)

      • init

        public void init()
        Description copied from interface: Component

        Called when a Component is first attached to a WindowManager. This means the Component should have valid return values from getApplication(), getLocaleContext(), getParent(). It is preferable to have all construction of the Component go here since a valid LocaleContext, Application object, etc., are available.

        When overriding this method, be sure to call the super class init(). init() is called only once for each Component. The parent component will have been init()ed before init() is called.

        NOTE: Do not call this method from application code. It is meant to be called by the WindowManager only.

        Specified by:
        init in interface Component
        Overrides:
        init in class ComponentImpl

      • setInline

        public ClickToEditComponent setInline(boolean inline)
                               throws UnsupportedOperationException
        Description copied from class: Container
        Set the inline property.

        This determines whether or not the Container is output as a SPAN or a DIV. The default is false for Containers. Be careful to avoid setting the container to inline then adding a block level element to the Container.

        Setting to true will only work for containers that do not have a layout since a layout results in a table being output.

        If Container.withHTMLElement(HTMLElement) is called, this is ignored.

        Overrides:
        setInline in class Container
        Parameters:
